<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-12-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-12-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="213" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d213">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">611.51G9/22</note>
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>)</head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-12-17">December 17, 1940</date>.</dateline></opener>
                    <p>During my conversation with the Foreign Minister today I spoke emphatically
                        on the matter of shipment of American-owned goods from Indochina, repeating
                        my representations of November 15 and 30, and in a signed note (no. 1714,
                        December 17, 1940<note n="15" xml:id="d213fn15"><hi rend="italic">Infra</hi>.</note>) decried the continued and unwarranted
                        interference.</p>
                    <closer><signed>J[<hi rend="smallcaps">oseph</hi>] C. G[<hi rend="smallcaps">rew</hi>]</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>